The defendant Telerick B Terrell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Operating Vehicle Without Owner's Consent (Knowing Passenger), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(4m).
  • Obstructing An Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Telerick B Terrell in court with attorney Nicholas M Weege.  Chad Wozniak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties prepared to proceed with sentencing. State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law. Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.

AS TO COUNT 5: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to count 6, with credit for 5 days served. Court STAYED the sentence(s) and placed the defendant on probation for 2 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 6: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to count 5. Court STAYED the sentence(s) and placed the defendant on probation for 2 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- Serve 30 days condition time in the House of Correction; STAYED pending use of agent. Court further allows huber for the condition time.
- Maintain absolute sobriety.
- Not to reside or be present where a firearm present in a car.
- No possession of illegal drugs unless prescribed by a doctor.
- Maintain full-time work or school or combination of both. 
- No contact with Jabri Powell.
- Provide a DNA sample. 

- Defendant to pay all mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharges during the period of probation. Failure to pay the costs and surcharges will result in a civil judgment.

- Court orders victim impact sealed and no contact order stating victim's name. 

- Court set restitution at zero.

*Court advised defendant of appellant rights.
*Court will grants expungement once completion of probation.

Defendant Telerick B Terrell in court with attorney Nicholas M Weege.  John J Rejowski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Parties have reached a resolution. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY as to COUNT 1 and 2.  

Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen deportation is possible. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived their rights.  Plea questionnaire, addendum and jury instructions received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Defendant advised again of bail conditions. Matter adjourned for sentencing hearing in Branch 4.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 19, 2022 at 02:30 pm.
